A morphology similar to hair scales was obtained after carbonation under the N2 atmosphere at 700 °C, as present in Fig. 2 a and b. The high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) image clearly shows the CQDs were randomly located in the hard carbon matrix (Fig. 2c and d). The CQDs were formed in-situ in the CQDHC during the synthesis of the electrode material. Therefore, the CQDs can only be partially extracted from the CQDHC by ethanol. According to HRTEM, the approximate density of the CQDs on the given area of a CQDHC plane was ∼0.034 cd/nm2 (Fig. S4a). The average size of CQDs in CQDHC was 2.27 nm (
Fig. S4b
). It shows that after high-temperature carbonation, the size of CQDs was maintained in the range of 2–10 nm (Fig. S4c). The average lattice spacing of CQDs calculated from HRTEM is 0.22 nm, consistent with the lattice spacing of CQDs extracted from the intermediate product as shown in Fig. S2b, which indicated that CQDs structure did not change during high-temperature pyrolysis. The commercial hard carbon material (CHC) did not show CQDs structure on the contrary (Fig. S5). The XRD pattern of CQDHC shows two broad peaks at about 23.5° and 44° (Fig. 3 a), corresponding to the (002) and (101) diffraction of a low degree of graphitization that fits with TEM characterization. These standard diffraction peaks belong to hexagonal graphite (JCPDS card no. 41–1487).

In addition to kinetics analysis, ex-situ TEM and mapping were conducted to verify the total capacitance contribution of K+ storage (

                           Fig. 6


                        ). As shown in Fig. 2d, the CQDs with interlayer space of 0.22 nm are randomly distributed in the CQDHC electrode in the pristine stage. After potassiation, the regularity near the CQDs becomes higher, and the CQDs were stably distributed in the hard carbon matrix. The interlayer space of hard carbon was 0.38 nm due to the K+ uniformly distributed in the electrode, verified by TEM mapping [36]. At the same time, it was clear that the lattice interspace of CQDs was slightly increased to 0.24 nm, which might be influenced by the K+ adsorbed at the surface of CQDs during the potassiation stage. After discharge, the K+ desorbed from the electrode and transferred back, meanwhile, the layered structure in most of the hard carbon disappeared while the rest was reduced to 0.32 nm, and the lattice interspace of CQDs was 0.22 nm which was the same as the original state (Fig. S8). The TEM mapping of CQDHC at the potassiation stage verified that K+ was uniformly absorbed into the CQDHC electrode.
